@zodwraith5745 Well, 9070 XT has 357 mm monolithic die size vs 346 mm multi-chip module on the 7800 XT, almost double the transistors at 53.9 billion vs 28.1 billion, and memory bandwidth increased to 644.6 GB/s from 624.1 GB/s with an extra 80 MHz base memory clock on reference model. 7800 XT sold new for $500-550 most of the time at Microcenter, Newegg, etc. So that's getting into 9070 non-XT pricing territory, and 9070 XT performs remarkably better according to testing in this review video, certainly worth $50+ better.

NVIDIA buyers seem to find exorbitant price hiking acceptable, so why is moderate price hiking not acceptable for AMD? I don't think its fair to single out AMD pricing here when NVIDIA has either an inferior product in the 5070 for almost as much money as a 9070 XT or a somewhat better product in the 5070 Ti for hundreds of dollars more in their current midrange lineup.

I just checked the VR Reddit and there's posts going back to last year saying they're running Quest and Vive headsets just fine on AMD GPU's. There were driver issues initially but AMD has fixed them since a while ago. So AMD not optimizing for VR is out of date advice. Some games are just optimized better on NVIDIA, but that's a software issue, not a hardware issue.

